        "id": 333
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-02T21:43:04Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The interrupt on ticks \u003d\u003d 0 was intentionally removed following Hadi\u0027s comment: setting an interrupt on every zero-timeout in sfdp_session_timer_update would fire on every TCP teardown with l4-lifecycle enabled, which is too expensive. The immediate interrupt now only lives in sfdp_expire_session_now. Also removed the unused tw parameter from sfdp_session_timer_update and updated all callers.",
      "parentUuid": "1a138a30_1f3f936d",
      "revId": "85b200902b3fa4e4614496f96728ac1cd365d214",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3ff1f822_47c0e8bd",
        "filename": "src/vnet/sfdp/timer/timer.h",
        "patchSetId": 18
      },
      "lineNbr": 128,
      "author": {
        "id": 361
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-03T11:04:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "But what if a dataplane service wants to effectively expire a session by setting its timeout to 0? Then it will not work?",
      "parentUuid": "dc626362_3972bf91",
      "revId": "85b200902b3fa4e4614496f96728ac1cd365d214",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ea7ec755_032edd24",
        "filename": "src/vnet/sfdp/timer/timer.h",
        "patchSetId": 18
      },
      "lineNbr": 128,
      "author": {
        "id": 3027
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-03T12:44:59Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "That will still work. If a dataplane service sets the timeout to 0, the session will now only be reaped/removed after the periodic call to \u0027sfdp-expire\u0027 (every 1s by default, configurable with SFDP_TIMER_INTERVAL).\n\nThe interrupt which was removed would invoke/schedule \u0027sfdp-expire\u0027 to run in the same main loop / worker loop iterations, which would quickly expire sessions. However, the downside was that \u0027sfdp-expire\u0027 could be scheduled at worst case for every frame/256 packets, if it least one packet was expired by a dataplane service, leading to a very high number of \u0027sfdp-expire\u0027 node calls.\n\nThe tradeoff by removing the interrupt here is that sessions expired by a dataplane service can take up-to \u0027SFDP_TIMER_INTERVAL\u0027 seconds longer to be removed/reaped.",
      "parentUuid": "3ff1f822_47c0e8bd",
      "revId": "85b200902b3fa4e4614496f96728ac1cd365d214",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
